The '''Hugh Lane Gallery''', officially '''Dublin City Gallery The Hugh Lane''' and originally the '''Municipal Gallery of Modern Art''', is an [[art gallery]] operated by [[Dublin City Council]] and its subsidiary the Hugh Lane Gallery Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dublincity.ie/sites/default/files/content/RecreationandCulture/ArtsOffice/HughLane/Documents/FinalCodeofGovernance.pdf|title=Code of Governance|publisher=Hugh Lane Gallery Trust|date=January 2014|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref> It is located in [[Charlemont House]] (built 1763) on [[Parnell Square]], [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].

The gallery was founded by Sir [[Hugh Lane]] on [[Harcourt Street]] in 1908, and is the first known public gallery of [[modern art]] in the world.{{cn|date=June 2015}} There is no admission fee and the gallery is completely wheelchair-accessible. The gallery was closed for reconstruction in 2004, and reopened in May 2006, with a new extension by Gilroy McMahon Architects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gilroymcmahon.com/cultural/projects/dublin-gallery.htm|title=PROJECTS: Cultural - The Hugh Lane Gallery|publisher=Gilroy McMahon Architects|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lmp.ie/newbuild/hughlane.html|title=Combining old and new at the Hugh Lane Art Gallery|publisher=Lee McCullough Consulting Engineers|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>

The museum has a permanent collection and hosts exhibitions, mostly by contemporary Irish artists. It has a dedicated [[Sean Scully]] room. [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]]'s studio was reconstructed in the gallery in 2001 after being dismantled and moved from London starting in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.francis-bacon.com/blog/francis-bacons-studio-lecture-at-tokyo-momat/|title=‘Francis Bacon’s Studio’ lecture at Tokyo MOMAT|publisher=Estate of Francis Bacon|date=2013-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whitehotmagazine.com/articles/studio-hugh-lane-gallery-dublin/337|title=Francis Bacon's studio, Hugh Lane Gallery, Dublin|author=Paul Tuthill|publisher=Whitehot Magazine|date=April 2007|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>
[[File:Dublin Francis Bacon Gallery The Hugh Lane756.jpg|right|frameless|Reconstruction of the Francis Bacon Studio at the Hugh Lane Gallery]]
The Hugh Lane is notable for its collection of French art, including works such as ''[[The Umbrellas (Renoir painting)|The Umbrellas]]'' (''Les Parapluies'') by [[Auguste Renoir]]; Portrait of Eva Gonzalès by [[Édouard Manet]], Jour d’Été by [[Berthe Morisot]] and View of Louveciennes by [[Camille Pissarro]].{{cn|date=June 2015}}

In 1992, the painting ''In The Omnibus'' by [[Honoré Daumier]] was stolen from the gallery, and recovered in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27394001|title=Stolen painting returned to Hugh Lane Gallery|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2014-05-13|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>

