{{Infobox settlement |name=Laslea |settlement_type=[[Communes of Romania|Commune]] |total_type=&nbsp; |image_skyline=Malmkrog Apafi Schloss 01.jpg |image_caption=Apafi manor in Mălâncrav |image_map=Laslea jud Sibiu.jpg |map_caption=Location of Laslea |subdivision_type=Country |subdivision_name={{flag|Romania}} |subdivision_type1=[[Counties of Romania|County]] |subdivision_name1=[[Sibiu County]] |population_total=3248 |population_as_of=2011 |population_footnotes=<ref>[http://www.sibiu.insse.ro/phpfiles/tab2_1_tot_etnie_SIBIU.pdf Romanian census data, 2011]; retrieved on March 15, 2012</ref> |coordinates = {{coord|46|13|N|24|39|E|region:RO|display=inline}} |pushpin_map=Romania |timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]|utc_offset=+2 |timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]|utc_offset_DST=+3 }} '''Laslea''' ({{lang-de|Grosslasseln}}; {{lang-hu|Szászszentlászló}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[Sibiu County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Florești, Laslea, Mălâncrav, Nou Săsesc and Roandola.
At the 2011 census, 61% of inhabitants were [[Romanians]], 30% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]], 7.5% [[Germans]] and 1% [[Hungarians]]. At the 2002 census, 76.2% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 7.2% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 5.7% [[Evangelical Lutheran Church of Romania|Evangelical Lutheran]], 5.2% [[Romanian Union Conference of Seventh-day Adventists|Seventh-day Adventist]], 2.6% [[Evangelical Church of Augustan Confession in Romania|Evangelical Church of Augustan Confession]] and 1.2% [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]].
[[Image:almakerek2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The apse]]
==Villages== {| class="wikitable" |- ! In [[Romanian language|Romanian]] ! In [[German language|German]] ! In [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] |- | Florești | Felsendorf | Földszin |- | Laslea | Grosslasseln | Szászszentlászló |- | Mălâncrav | Malmkrog | Almakerék |- | Nou Săsesc | Neudorf | Apaújfalu |- | Roandola | Rauthal | Rudály |} Mălâncrav is a village in Laslea commune. An asphalt road of 13&nbsp;km leads to the village. In the village there is a small community of [[Transylvanian Saxon]]s.
Here some of the most significant [[Gothic art|Gothic]] [[mural]]s in [[Transylvania]] aside from those at [[Ghelința]] in [[Covasna County]] are found.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
The Saxon [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church has early 14th-century Gothic murals in the [[apse]]. 15th-century ones are found in the [[nave]] and a 15th-century late Gothic [[altar]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
In later centuries the Apafi family (Hungarian nobles in Transylvania) buried their dead in the church since they had overlordship in the village. Although the sarcophagi were removed (one of [[Mihaly Apafi]] is now in [[Budapest]]'s [[Hungarian National Museum]]). The locality was not part of the autonomous Saxon territory Although until the 1970s when it was populated by Germans.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
==Prince of Wales and sustainable tourism== In 2006, The [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]] bought and restored two 18th century [[Transylvanian Saxon]] houses in the villages of Mălâncrav and [[Viscri]] to help protect the unique way of life that has existed for hundreds of years and promote [[sustainable tourism]].
The buildings have been sensitively restored and converted into guesthouses for tourists. They remain in keeping with the surrounding architecture and feature a number of Transylvanian antiques but with modern facilities where possible.
The renovation of these buildings has helped provide a sustainable future for the people of rural Transylvania while also enabling residents to maintain their traditional way of life.
